fields.name: axis_member
fields.documentation: Description of a given ensemble member. It will normally be related to a specific ensemble requirement. Note that start dates can be extracted directly from the simulations and do not need to be recorded with an axis member description.

fields.name: conformance
fields.documentation: A specific conformance. Describes how a particular numerical requirement has been implemented. Will normally be linked from an ensemble descriptor.

fields.name: ensemble
fields.documentation: Generic ensemble definition. Holds the definition of how the various ensemble members have been configured. If ensemble axes are not present, then this is either a single member ensemble, or part of an uber ensemble.

fields.name: ensemble_axis
fields.documentation: Defines the meaning of r/i/p indices in an ensemble.

fields.name: ensemble_member
fields.documentation: An ensemble may be a complicated interplay of axes, for example, r/i/p, not all of which are populated, so we need a list of the actual simulations and how they map onto the ensemble axes.

fields.name: parent_simulation
fields.documentation: Defines the relationship between a simulation and its parent.

fields.name: uber_ensemble
fields.documentation: An ensemble made up of other ensembles. Often used where parts of an ensemble were run by different institutes. Could also be used when a new experiment is designed which can use ensemble members from previous experiments and/or projects.

fields.name: dataset
fields.documentation: Dataset discovery information.

fields.name: downscaling
fields.documentation: Defines a downscaling activity.

fields.name: input_dataset
fields.documentation: An input dataset is used as within another component (such as a model). It comprises an original, source dataset plus any modifications requirted to use it in the relevant component.

fields.name: simulation
fields.documentation: Simulation class provides the integrating link about what models were run and wny. In many cases this should be auto-generated from output file headers.

fields.name: variable_collection
fields.documentation: A collection of variables within the scope of a code or process element.

fields.name: axis_member
fields.documentation: PLACEHOLDER for the real axis_member.

fields.name: domain_requirements
fields.documentation: Properties of the domain which needs to be simulated, extent and/or resolution.

fields.name: ensemble_requirement
fields.documentation: Defines an experiment ensemble.

fields.name: forcing_constraint
fields.documentation: Identifies a model forcing constraint.

fields.name: initialisation_requirement
fields.documentation: A requirement on how a particular simulation should be initialised.

fields.name: multi_ensemble
fields.documentation: In the case of multiple ensemble axes, defines how they are set up and ordered.

fields.name: numerical_experiment
fields.documentation: Defines a numerical experiment.

fields.name: numerical_requirement
fields.documentation: A numerical requirement associated with a numerical experiment.

fields.name: output_requirement
fields.documentation: Provides details of what output is required and when from an experiment.

fields.name: project
fields.documentation: Describes a scientific project.

fields.name: simulation_plan
fields.documentation: Describes a simulation that needs to be run.

fields.name: start_date_ensemble
fields.documentation: Defines an experiment ensemble with multiple start dates.

fields.name: temporal_constraint
fields.documentation: A spatio-temporal constraint on a numerical experiment.

fields.name: drs_atomic_dataset
fields.documentation: An entity in a DRS file system.

fields.name: drs_ensemble_identifier
fields.documentation: Identifies a 'response ensemble' realisation using the semantic content ofa 'run_variant_id'.

fields.name: drs_experiment
fields.documentation: An encoding of a drs experiment_id.

fields.name: drs_geographical_indicator
fields.documentation: Specifies geographical subsets described by bounding boxes or by named regions. One of spatial domain or bounding box must appear.

fields.name: drs_publication_dataset
fields.documentation: PLACEHOLDER for the real drs_publication_dataset.

fields.name: drs_simulation_identifier
fields.documentation: That part of the DRS which identifies the response to the experiment: the simulation.

fields.name: drs_temporal_identifier
fields.documentation: Provides information about temporal subsetting and/or averaging. If only N1 is present, it a temporal instant, If N1-N2 are present with no suffix, it is a temporal subset, If N1-N2 with a suffix are present, then some sort of temporal averaging has been applied across the period.

fields.name: component_performance
fields.documentation: Describes the simulation rate of a component in seconds per model day. Based on "CPMIP: Measurements of Real Computational Performance of Earth System Models" (Balaji et. al.)

fields.name: compute_pool
fields.documentation: Homogeneous pool of nodes within a computing machine.

fields.name: machine
fields.documentation: A computer/system/platform/machine which is used for simulation.

fields.name: partition
fields.documentation: A major partition (component) of a computing system (aka machine).

fields.name: performance
fields.documentation: Describes the properties of a performance of a configured model on a particular system/machine. Based on "CPMIP: Measurements of Real Computational Performance of Earth System Models" (Balaji et. al. 2016, doi:10.5194/gmd-2016-197, http://www.geosci-model-dev-discuss.net/gmd-2016-197/)

fields.name: storage_pool
fields.documentation: Homogeneous storage pool on a computing machine.

fields.name: storage_volume
fields.documentation: Platform storage volume and units.

fields.name: conservation_properties
fields.documentation: Describes how prognostic variables are conserved.

fields.name: detail
fields.documentation: Provides details of specific properties of a process, sub-process, key properties, etc., there are two possible specialisations expected: (1) A detail_vocabulary is identified, and a cardinality is assigned to that for possible responses, or (2) Detail is used to provide a collection for a set of properties which are defined in the sub-class. However, those properties must have a type which is selected from the classmap (that is, standard 'non-es-doc' types).

fields.name: discretisation
fields.documentation: Collection of properties related to method of process discretisation.

fields.name: extent
fields.documentation: Key scientific characteristics of the grid use to simulate a specific domain. Note that the extent does not itself describe a grid, so, for example, a polar stereographic grid may have an extent of northern boundary 90N, southern boundary 45N, but the fact that it is PS comes from the grid_type.

fields.name: grid
fields.documentation: This describes the numerical grid used for the calculations. It is not necessarily the grid upon which the data is output. It is NOT the resolution, which is a property of a specific domain.

fields.name: iso_extent
fields.documentation: Extent on a latitude-longitudinal grid - to aid traditional cartesian discovery.

fields.name: key_properties
fields.documentation: High level list of key properties. It can be specialised in extension packages using the detail extensions.

fields.name: model
fields.documentation: A model component: can be executed standalone, and has as scientific description available via a link to a science.domain document. (A configured model can be understood in terms of a simulation, a model, and a configuration.).

fields.name: process
fields.documentation: Provides structure for description of a process simulated within a particular area (or domain/realm/component) of a model. This will often be subclassed within a specific implementation so that constraints can be used to ensure that the process details requested are consistent with project requirements for information.

fields.name: resolution
fields.documentation: Describes the computational spatial resolution of a component or process. Not intended to replace or replicate the output grid description. When it appears as part of a process description, provide only properties that differ from parent domain. Note that this is supposed to capture gross features of the grid, we expect many grids will have different variable layouts, those should be described in the grid description, and the exact resolution is not required. Note that many properties are not appropriate for adaptive grids.

fields.name: scientific_realm
fields.documentation: Scientific area of a numerical model - usually a sub-model or component. Can also be known as a realm.

fields.name: sub_process
fields.documentation: Provides structure for description of part of process simulated within a particular area (or domain/realm/component) of a model. Typically this will be a part of process which shares common properties. It will normally be sub classed within a specific implementation so that constraints can be used to ensure that the process details requested are consistent with projects requirements for information.

fields.name: tuning
fields.documentation: Method used to optimise equation parameters in model component (aka 'tuning').

fields.name: cimtext
fields.documentation: Provides a text class which supports plaintext, html, and friends (or will do).

fields.name: citation
fields.documentation: An academic reference to published work.

fields.name: doc_reference
fields.documentation: Specialisation of online resource for link between CIM documents, whether the remote document exists when complete, or not.

fields.name: extra_attribute
fields.documentation: An extra attribute with key and value needed to encode further information not in the CIM2 domain model or specialisation. Typical use case: in parsing data and encoding attributes found in data.

fields.name: online_resource
fields.documentation: A minimal approximation of ISO19115 CI_ONLINERESOURCE, provides a link and details of how to use that link.

fields.name: party
fields.documentation: Implements minimal material for an ISO19115-1 (2014) compliant party. For our purposes this is a much better animal than the previous responsibleParty which munged roles together with people. Note we have collapsed CI_Contact, CI_Individual and CI_Organisation as well as the abstract CI_Party.

fields.name: quality_review
fields.documentation: Assertions as to the completeness and quality of a document.

fields.name: responsibility
fields.documentation: Implements the ISO19115-1 (2014) CI_Responsibility (which replaces responsibleParty). Combines a person and their role in doing something.

fields.name: composition
fields.documentation: Describes how component variables are coupled together either to/from other SoftwareComponents or external data files. The variables specified by a component's composition must be owned by that component, or a child of that component; child components cannot couple together parent variables.

fields.name: development_path
fields.documentation: Describes the software development path for this model/component.

fields.name: entry_point
fields.documentation: Describes a function or subroutine of a SoftwareComponent. BFG will use these EntryPoints to define a schedule of subroutine calls for a coupled model. Currently, a very basic schedule can be approximated by using the 'proceeds' and 'follows' attributes, however a more complete system is required for full BFG compatibility. Every EntryPoint can have a set of arguments associated with it. These reference (previously defined) variables.

fields.name: gridspec
fields.documentation: Fully defines the computational grid used.

fields.name: software_component
fields.documentation: An embedded piece of software that does not normally function as a standalone model (although it may be used standalone in a test harness).

fields.name: variable
fields.documentation: An instance of a model software variable which may be prognostic or diagnostic, and which is available as a connection to other software components. Note that these variables may only exist within the software workflow as interim quantities or coupling endpoints. Input and output variables will be a subset of these software variables.

fields.name: calendar
fields.documentation: Describes the calendar required/used in an experiment/simulation. This class is based on the calendar attributes and properties found in the CF netCDF conventions.

fields.name: date_time
fields.documentation: A date or time. Either in simulation time with the simulation calendar, or with reference to a simulation start, in which case the datetime is an interval after the start date.

fields.name: irregular_dateset
fields.documentation: A set of irregularly spaced times, provided as a comma separated string of yyyy-mm-dd in the appropriate calendar.

fields.name: regular_timeset
fields.documentation: A regularly spaced set of times.

fields.name: time_period
fields.documentation: A time period/interval (aka temporal extent).

fields.documentation: Coupling cost measures the overhead caused by coupling. This can include the cost of the coupling algorithm itself (which may involve grid interpolation and computation of transfer coefficients for conservative coupling) as well as load imbalance.
